      About this item

      • Effortless Setup: Start setup instantly by scanning the Matter QR code using your smartphone's camera or smart home application, simplifying the installation for immediate use. Matter Hub Required. Stocking Stuffer idea for the holidays.
      • Matter Hub Required. A Matter-compatible hub is required for successful setup. Most leading smart home hubs and assistants are compatible out-of-the-box with Matter – Apple HomeKit, Google Home, Amazon Alexa, and Samsung SmartThings. Refer to smart home details with manufacturer
      • Secure Wi-Fi Connectivity: Utilizes your home's secure Wi-Fi network (WPA2), ensuring reliable and secure connectivity for convenient control from anywhere.
      • Reliable Local Control: Operates independently even without internet connectivity. Communicates directly with a Matter controller, ensuring faster and more reliable local command processing.
      • Plug-and-Play Smart Control: Instantly gain smart control of attached devices by simply plugging into an existing outlet, allowing for easy integration into your smart home setup without complex installations.

      Product Description

      Take comfort in the convenience of controlling your lights from any smart device, whether you’re home or not. The Smart Plug-In Switch, 2nd Gen Wi-Fi enables you to control your lamps or other plugged-in devices and set scenes and schedules from any Matter-compliant smart home platform. Combining classic design and advanced functionality with a simple connection to your existing smart home solution using your home’s existing wireless network, Smart Lighting from the radiant® Collection sets the exact lighting you want – when and where you need it.

      How customer reviews and ratings work

      Customer Reviews, including Product Star Ratings help customers to learn more about the product and decide whether it is the right product for them.

      To calculate the overall star rating and percentage breakdown by star, we don’t use a simple average. Instead, our system considers things like how recent a review is and if the reviewer bought the item on Amazon. It also analyzed reviews to verify trustworthiness.

      5 out of 5 stars
      HomeKit Compatible and Seriously Impressed
      This outlet was set up within seconds of scanning the QR code on the back to use with Apple HomeKit. No third-party app installs, no waiting, it just worked, immediately. I’ve had so much trouble with WeMo plugs and can’t believe how easy this was at half the price. I do have a HomePod Mini and Apple TV 4K (3rd generation) that act as thread border routers, so this might be the difference and you’d need a compatible device for the thread capability. That said, I would definitely would buy again.

        As many others have mentioned, the Meross plugs have issues, that firmware updates have attempted and failed to address. Interestingly these legrand plugs are smaller in size (squaring up with the leading edge of a decora faceplate and not overlapping) yet have identical electrical ratings and certification, the same weight (while being smaller, which indicates thicker plastic or heavier components, implied by the heartier but still soft click of the relay) and do not suffer from the chronic disconnect issues plaguing Meross. My router indicates the signal quality to the legrand outlets is substantially better than the Meross, in the same outlet, tested individually, the legrand measured -67 and the Meross -74. While neither of these values are great, the difference is quite large all things considered.

        The only notable downsize to these legrand outlets is the 'control' app (which you don't need and I recommend you don't bother with) because it doesn't support these outlets without a Netatmo or rebranded legrand hub. I suspect legrand partnered with netatmo to develope these outlets as they appear identical to the netatmo's. The reason I consider this a downside is there is no way to update the firmware if a security exploit is discovered, but I suspect if it is that critical they will allow the app to discover devices on a network without requiring a hub. I mean hey, I've been through 3 firmware updates on the Meross plugs over the last 2 years and they haven't really made a difference whatsoever.

        Overall this is an obvious no brainer. They were a cinch to add as a HomeKit device and have functioned perfectly for 3 weeks.
